IRS e-News for Small Businesses

Issue 2007-22

June 20, 2007

In this Issue:

1. Use New Agent Appointment Form 2678; Discard Prior Versions
2. Offering Money Services?  Register with the Government
3. Find Business Topics Fast Using New Index
4. Recommend e-News for Small Businesses
5. Recent IRS Announcements for Small Businesses

1. Use New Agent Appointment Form 2678; Discard Prior Versions

Employers, payers and agents should begin using the May 2007 revision of Form 2678, Employer/Payer Appointment of Agent, and discard prior versions to avoid delays in getting IRS approval. The redesigned and retitled Form 2678 contains several enhancements that clarify and simplify the authorization process.

Download Form 2678 from IRS.gov, or call (800) 829-3676 to request copies by mail. Instructions and the IRS mailing address are included with the two-page form.

Related Link:
Form 2678, Employer/Payer Appointment of Agent http://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/f2678.pdf

2. Offering Money Services?  Register with the Government

Businesses offering money services including wire transfers, currency exchange, money orders, traveler’s checks, and check cashing may be required to register with the U.S. Department of Treasury.  

Businesses have 180 days from the date they begin operating as an MSB to register using FinCEN Form 107, Registration of Money Services Business. The registration is good for two calendar years and is renewable by December 31 of the second year using the same form. 

Civil and criminal penalties may be imposed for failure to register. 

FinCEN Form 107 can also be ordered by calling (800) 829-3676.

Related Links:
Money Service Businesses http://www.msb.gov/  
Money Services Business Registration Requirements http://www.irs.gov/businesses/small/article/0,,id=158384,00.html
Form 107, Registration of Money Services http://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/ffc107.pdf   
FinCEN http://www.fincen.gov

4. Find Business Topics Fast Using New Index

Researching IRS.gov for your business needs is now even easier with an A-Z Index for Businesses on the Small Business and Self-Employed One-Stop Resource page. 

Business topics are arranged by business type, business subjects, and alphabetically to help business owners find information fast.

Related Links:
A-Z Index for Businesses http://www.irs.gov/businesses/small/article/0,,id=154770,00.html
Smll Business and Self-Employed One-Stop Resource http://www.irs.gov/businesses/small/index.html

5. Recommend e-News for Small Businesses 

If you know a business acquaintance, your accountant, or tax preparer who could benefit from reading e-News for Small Businesses, please forward this week’s issue or this link to them to subscribe.

Related link:
Subscribe to e-News for Small Businesses http://www.irs.gov/businesses/small/content/0,,id=154826,00.html.

